**2. Wire it up in `Program.cs`:**

```csharp
var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);

// Add Problem Details support + custom handler
builder.Services.AddProblemDetails();
builder.Services.AddExceptionHandler<GlobalExceptionHandler>();

var app = builder.Build();

// Must be early in the pipeline
app.UseExceptionHandler();

// Your endpoints — no try-catch needed
app.MapGet("/items/{id}", (int id) =>
{
    if (id < 0) throw new ArgumentException("ID must be positive.");
    if (id == 0) throw new KeyNotFoundException("Item not found.");
    return Results.Ok(new { Id = id, Name = "Widget" });
});

app.Run();
```

**How it works:**

| Exception | Status | Detail shown? |
|-----------|--------|---------------|
| `KeyNotFoundException` | 404 | Yes (message) |
| `ArgumentException` | 400 | Yes (message) |
| `InvalidOperationException` | 409 | Yes (message) |
| Anything else | 500 | Generic only |

The `IExceptionHandler` interface (added in .NET 8) integrates with `UseExceptionHandler()` middleware, catching all unhandled exceptions globally. For 500s, the exception message is suppressed to avoid leaking internals — only `"An unexpected error occurred."` is returned. The response `Content-Type` is automatically `application/problem+json`.
